### Struct Embedding

Go supports struct embedding (composition), not inheritance.

### Basic Embedding

```go
type Base struct {
    ID int
}

func (b Base) GetID() int {
    return b.ID
}

type User struct {
    Base               // embedded
    Name string
}

func main() {
    u := User{Base: Base{ID: 1}, Name: "Alice"}
    fmt.Println(u.ID)        // 1 (promoted field)
    fmt.Println(u.GetID())   // 1 (promoted method)
}
```

### Method Promotion

Methods of the embedded struct are promoted to the embedding struct:

```go
type Logger struct{}

func (l Logger) Log(msg string) {
    fmt.Println("[LOG]:", msg)
}

type Service struct {
    Logger  // embedded
    Name string
}

func main() {
    s := Service{Name: "API"}
    s.Log("server started") // promoted method
}
```

### Field Shadowing

If the outer struct has a field with the same name, it shadows the inner:

```go
type A struct {
    X int
}

type B struct {
    A
    X string // shadows A.X
}

func main() {
    b := B{A: A{X: 10}, X: "hello"}
    fmt.Println(b.X)   // "hello"
    fmt.Println(b.A.X) // 10
}
```

### Multiple Embedding

```go
type Reader struct{}
func (r Reader) Read() string { return "data" }

type Writer struct{}
func (w Writer) Write(data string) { fmt.Println("wrote:", data) }

type ReadWriter struct {
    Reader
    Writer
}

func main() {
    rw := ReadWriter{}
    data := rw.Read()   // from Reader
    rw.Write(data)      // from Writer
}
```

### Embedding vs Inheritance

| Aspect | Go Embedding | Classical Inheritance |
|--------|-------------|---------------------|
| Type relationship | Has-a | Is-a |
| Method override | Shadowing | Overriding |
| Polymorphism | Via interfaces | Via class hierarchy |
| Complexity | Simple | Complex |

> **Key Point:** Go uses composition over inheritance. Embedding promotes fields and methods to the outer type, providing code reuse without class hierarchies.

